Reflecting on December 5, 2020
———
#SWIPE ⬅️
At the height of the pandemic (Art Basel/Miami Art Week was cancelled that year), by the grace of God I was able to have an in-person event at the @conradhotels in Brickell to celebrate the release of my first self-published book of photography,
TO MIAMI, with LOVE - 256 pages of Black & White photography capturing and chronicling what we were going thru in Miami in real time with COVID and George Floyd protests and the shut down of the hospitality industry. The CONRAD hotel gave me the entire restaurant level of their hotel and allowed me the opportunity to curate something special for the people. @alexfinniewplg from @local10news did the Q&A with me, and some folks who came, purchased books on site. 

That was two years ago today.  I could never have imagined two years later that my work would be considered officially part of Miami’s history and on display at @historymiami museum. 

It’s hard sometimes not to think about the people who told me I shouldn’t and couldn’t and wouldn’t be able to do this; but at the same time, I took that negative energy and turned it into LOVE. 

Happy TWO Year Anniversary to the book that changed my life.

I’m grateful to everyone who was involved in making this happen.

Please watch the videos in the SWIPE 🙏🏾

For the better part of the last decade, Rahsaan Alexander, professionally known as DJ FLY GUY, had been a fixture behind the turntables at the most prominent nightclubs in Miami’s nightlife scene. Faced with a global health crisis, the shutdown of his industry, and brewing social unrest, Rahsaan turned his creative energies to a passion he once explored as a high school senior at Miami Killian: photography.

Now through Feb. 12, three exhibitions at HistoryMiami Museum are exploring critical periods throughout Black Miami’s history through photography, film and audio.

Locals who have not yet visited the exhibitions, which were each unveiled at separate times last year, have one last chance to see them before they come down.

A third exhibition, “CAPTURE: A Portrait of the Pandemic” by photographer and DJ Rahsaan “Fly Guy” Alexander, a Miami native, chronicles life in Miami during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020 and local protests in the wake of George Floyd’s murder. Alexander’s photo exhibition, also featured in the Times last year, includes the short documentary film “PIVOT: A 2020 Story.”

“One hundred years from now or 200 years from now, people will look back and reflect on what the pandemic in 2020 was like and they will have these photos.”

Today marks the One Year Anniversary of my largest photography exhibition to date: CAPTURE: A Portrait of the Pandemic. To read more about what that exhibit was about, click the link in my bio. But for now, I’d like to just say how appreciative I am to everyone who played a part in bringing this vision to fruition. To the entire staff at @historymiami museum, you all were amazing from the very first meeting, to the final exhibition day.  Those 6 months of having my work on display there was so incredible for me, my family & friends and those close to me. To @noahsblues and @hamptonartlovers , thank you for inspiring me to surpass even my own visions. To @the_m_network , it was a pleasure to work with you. To @eyekon_photography , thank you for answering the call numerous times from before the first image was hung up, to the dsy of the final showing. To @djcommish thank u flying in from NY to DJ opening night.  At the risk of making this caption way longer than originally intended, I’ll wrap it up here but… just one more thing

To every friend, fan & supporter of mine who took the time to come see the exhibit in person and get a first-hand account of what my blood, sweat & tears created, which is now officially a part of the city of Miami’s HISTORY… I thank each & everyone of you from the depths of my soul.  The older, and hopefully wiser I get, I’m learning it’s not about who never came or didn’t/doesn’t show up for you. It’s about who DID/does. Ya’ll DID. You know who you are…And i am grateful. To @tinamene this began with you and @nola.11.11 and you both believing in my vision, there aren’t enough words to express the gratitude 🙏🏾 and i can’t forget the good folks over at @artfulprinters

She had this mixtape out called TWENTY90s and from the moment I heard it, I thought she was amazing. Songs like “Voodoo Dolls” & “Tryna Wife” had me thinking she was a hybrid of Missy Elliott mixed with Nicole Wray.  I remember one early performance she did at ROOM SERVICE where I played her music and I knew I had to work with her on a project of my own. She blessed me with some vocals on a song I called Supa Dupa Fly on my Machine Gun Rap mixtape. It was over a Missy Elliott beat but it later got put over an original track produced by @loaditupcarl and ended up as the first single off my GENIUSLAND album.  Even played the song during one of my guest DJ mixes on @99jamzmiami (big no-no 🤣). I say all this to say… to see where she is today as the first artist on @diddy LOVE RECORDS @loverecords label and how amazing her new EP “Songs for Women, Free Game for Ni**as is, I’m glad we get to celebrate her today at @doowopparty as part of our 2yr Anniversary.  Because when it comes to new R&B, she is a breath of fresh air !! Salute JOZZY!

𝐁𝐏𝐌: 𝐁𝐄𝐀𝐓𝐒, 𝐏𝐈𝐂𝐒 & 𝐌𝐀𝐒𝐓𝐄𝐑𝐒 𝐛𝐲 𝐑𝐚𝐡𝐬𝐚𝐚𝐧 “𝐅𝐋𝐘 𝐆𝐔𝐘“ 𝐀𝐥𝐞𝐱𝐚𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐫 is a three-part visual art series highlighting and bringing awareness to the mental, emotional, and psychological tolls taken on DJs who have committed much of their careers and passions to enteraining audiences night after night; for years.  The goal is to ultimately humanize the artist (which is the DJ) to the general public in hopes of giving insight into the struggles and complexicites shared by countless DJs around the world in a post-covid time.

In addition to the exhibition there will be an artist talk with DJ FLY GUY and VIBE magazine Editor-In-Chief Datwon Thomas @datwon at 3:30pm; moderated by Dr James Peterson.
